          en: "Spherification, pioneered by Ferran Adrià, uses sodium alginate (from seaweed) mixed into soup which is then dropped into a calcium chloride or calcium lactate bath. The calcium ions cross-link with alginate to form a gel membrane around droplets, creating caviar-like spheres filled with liquid soup. When bitten, they burst to release concentrated flavor. This modernist technique creates stunning visual and textural contrasts - imagine pea soup 'caviar' floating on consommé, or tomato soup spheres that explode with flavor.",
